is surname is also common in south and east Scotland and in Ireland, where it is sometimes found in the Gaelicized form <b>Pléamonn</b>.","German: variant of   Flemming  , cognate with 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Flemings","meanings":["English: plural form of   Fleming  .","Americanized form of Flemish <b>Vleminckx</b>: patronymic from <b>Vleminck</b>, an ethnic name for someone from Flanders, Middle Dutch <i>vleminc</i>."]},{"name":"Flanders","meanings":["English: ethnic name from Middle English <i>Fla(u)ndres</i> ‘Flanders’, denoting someone from Flanders, a historical region covering parts of modern-day Belgium, France, and the Netherlands. Compare   Fleming  ."]},{"name":"Fleeman","meanings":["English: variant of   Fleming  ."]},{"name":"Flemming","meanings":["German: ethnic name for someone from Flanders, Middle High German <i>vlaeminc</i>. People from Flanders spread throughout Germany, as well as England, in the Middle Ages as clothmakers and dyers.","English: variant of   Fleming  ."]},{"name":"Flamenco","meanings":["Spanish: ethnic name from <i>flamenco</i> ‘Fleming, Flemish person’ (see   Fleming  )."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John Fleming II was born about 1275, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, William Fleming III, was 27 and his mother, Alice, was 36. He had at least 3 sons with Isabella de la Mare. He died before 1351, in his hometown."},"et":{"Abt 1275–Bef 1351":"umbes 1275–enne 1351","1273–1314":"1273–1314","1275–1351":"1275–1351","–1356":"–1356","1300–1360":"1300–1360","–Male":"Surnud","1250–1307":"1250–1307","1240–Female":"1240–Surnud","1275":"1275","1351":"1351","1240":"1240","1273":"1273","1250":"1250","1360":"1360","Bef 1351":"enne 1351","1314":"1314","Abt 1300":"umbes 1300","1356":"1356","1300":"1300","Abt 1275":"umbes 1275","6 May 1307":"6. mai 1307","1307":"1307","Yorkshire, England":"Yorks